    <Grid Background="#FFFDFDFD">
        <ScrollViewer>
            <TextBlock x:Name="textBlock" Margin="0" TextWrapping="Wrap" FontSize="14" Height="920"><Run FontWeight="Bold" Text="&#x9;"/><Run Foreground="#FF0017FF" FontWeight="Bold" Text="&#x9;&#x9;&#x9;"/><Run Foreground="#FF0017FF" FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="24" Text="Mathematics"/><LineBreak/><Run Text=" &#x9;&#x9;"/><InlineUIContainer>
            		<Image


            			Width="225" Source="/Kerbal Space Program Tools;component/Images/Terminology/Cartesian.png" x:Name="image" Height="205"/>


            	</InlineUIContainer><Run Text="&#x9;&#x9;"/><InlineUIContainer>
            		<Image


            			Width="210" Source="/Kerbal Space Program Tools;component/Images/Terminology/Polar.png" x:Name="image2" Height="205"/>


            	</InlineUIContainer><LineBreak/><Run Foreground="#FF0017FF" FontWeight="Bold" Text="1) Elliptical"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="    Oval shaped, often in reference to your orbit."/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold"/><LineBreak/><Run Foreground="#FF0017FF" FontWeight="Bold" Text="2) Hyperbolic"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="    Open smooth curve, often in reference to escape trajectories."/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold"/><LineBreak/><Run Foreground="#FF0017FF" FontWeight="Bold" Text="3) Normal vector"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="    A vector perpendicular to a plane."/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold"/><LineBreak/><Run Foreground="#FF0017FF" FontWeight="Bold" Text="4) Scalar"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="    A single value without a direction. Scalars are usually followed by a u"/><Run Text="nit of measurement that tells what the scalar's dimension is. eg 3 m/s, 3 m,3 s are scalar: they have units which denote speed, length/distance, and time respectively, but have no direction."/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold"/><LineBreak/><Run Foreground="#FF0017FF" FontWeight="Bold" Text="5) Vector"/><Run FontWeight="Bold" Text="&#x9;&#x9;&#x9;&#x9;"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="    A set of a direction and a value. eg. heading (direction) and speed together give a velocity. How a vector is expressed depends on what the coordinate system is, and how many dimensions are taken into consideration. &lt;35°, 12&gt; is a two dimensional polar vector, where &lt;14, 9, -20&gt; is"/><Run Text=" "/><Run Text="a three dimensional Cartesian vector. There are other coordinate systems but these are the most utilized."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="    &lt;35°, 12&gt; looks like an arrow which is 12 units long, starting from the origin (zero, angle does not matter because it is a point with no length) and ending at a point 35° from the base axis (typically the x-axis, positive angles progress counter-clockwise)"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="    &lt;14, 9, -20&gt; looks like an arrow starting from the origin (&lt;0,0,0&gt;) and ending at a point where the x coordinate is at 14, the y coordinate = 9 and the z coordinate = -20. "/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="    The upside to using Cartesian coordinates is that you know exactly where the terminal position is, but it is more difficult to figure the length, however in polar coordinates it is trivial to find the length, the downside is its more difficult to know the position. "/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="    The following physical qualities are all vectors: "/><Run FontWeight="Bold" Text="velocity, acceleration, force"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="A 3D coordinate systems needs:"/><LineBreak/><LineBreak/><Run Text="    A point of reference. This is your origin."/><LineBreak/><Run Text="    3 base-vectors. These define your base unit of measurement along the axis and the direction of said axis."/><LineBreak/><Run Text="    A mix of 3 scalars, that could be either angles or co-ordinat"/><Run Text="es to express locations in your co-ordinate space."/><LineBreak/><Run Text="  &#x9;&#x9;&#x9;"/><Run Text=" &#x9;&#x9; &#x9;"/><Run Text="&#x9;&#x9; "/></TextBlock>


        </ScrollViewer>
    </Grid>
</Page>
